<div class=content-block-section>
    <div class="container" >


        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-6 col-12">
                


    <article class="richtext-content " >
        <h3 style="text-align: center;">CT Paid Leave (CTPL)</h3>
<p>CT Paid Leave is a law that provides covered workers with income replacement benefits when they are out of work for certain qualifying family or health reasons, provided they meet specific eligibility requirements. <b>CT Paid Leave does NOT provide job protected leave</b>, which is the right to return to your same job, or an equivalent one, when your leave ends. </p>
    </article>




            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-6 col-12">
                


    <article class="richtext-content " >
        <h3 style="text-align: center;">Family and Medical Leave Acts (FMLA)</h3>
<p>The Family and Medical Leave Acts are laws that ensure that an employer returns an eligible worker who takes time away from their job for a qualifying reason to their same job, or an equivalent one, when they return from their leave. There is a <a rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.dol.gov/agencies/whd/fmla" target="_blank" aria-label="Opens the Federal FMLA web page in a new window">federal FMLA</a> and <a rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://portal.ct.gov/DOLUI/newfmlaguidance" target="_blank" aria-label="Opens the CT FMLA web page in a new window">Connecticut FMLA</a>. A worker must apply directly to their employer for job protected leave under one or both laws. </p>
    </article>




            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="margin-b-16"></div>


<div class=content-block-section>
